## 5. Pointers to Structures

Pointers to structures are a special type of pointer that allows you to point to a structure.

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

typedef struct {
    char name[100];
    int status;
} person;

int main(int argc, char *argv[]) {
    // allocate a new person and set status to 0
	person *p = (person *)malloc(sizeof(person));
	p->status = 0;

    // allocate a new pointer to a structure and set it to point to p
	person *pp = (person *)malloc(sizeof(person));
	*pp = *p;

    // print the status of the person
	printf("status: %d\n", p->status);

    // set the status to 1
	p->status = 1;

    // print the status of the person
	printf("status: %d\n", p->status);

    // print the status of the person through the pointer
	printf("status: %d\n", (*pp).status);

    // free the person
	free(p);

    return 0;
}
```

Output:

```
status: 0
status: 1
status: 1
```

